# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: load-cells-strain
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] In engineering, **deformation** is the change in size or shape of an object when subjected to force, and may be *elastic* or *plastic* depending on whether the deformation is reversible when the actuating force is removed.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] An object's intrinsic resistance to deformation is known as its *stiffness* or *rigidity*.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] If the deformation is negligible under stress, the object is said to be *rigid*; conversely, it is said to be *flexible* or *pliable*.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] The relationship between stress and strain is generally linear and reversible up until the yield point and the deformation is elastic.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Elasticity in materials occurs when applied stress does not surpass the energy required to break molecular bonds, allowing the material to deform reversibly and return to its original shape once the stress is removed.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] The linear relationship for a material is known as Young's modulus.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Above the yield point, some degree of permanent distortion remains after unloading and is termed plastic deformation.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] The determination of the stress and strain throughout a solid object is given by the field of strength of materials and for a structure by structural analysis.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] In the above figure, it can be seen that the compressive loading (indicated by the arrow) has caused deformation in the cylinder so that the original shape (dashed lines) has changed (deformed) into one with bulging sides.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] The sides bulge because the material, although strong enough to not crack or otherwise fail, is not strong enough to support the load without change.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] As a result, the material is forced out laterally.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Internal forces (in this case at right angles to the deformation) resist the applied load.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Depending on the type of material, size and geometry of the object, and the forces applied, various types of deformation may result.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] The image to the right shows the engineering stress vs. strain diagram for a typical ductile material such as steel.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Different deformation modes may occur under different conditions, as can be depicted using a deformation mechanism map.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Permanent deformation is irreversible; the deformation stays even after removal of the applied forces, while the temporary deformation is recoverable as it disappears after the removal of applied forces.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Temporary deformation is also called **elastic** deformation, while the permanent deformation is called **plastic** deformation.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] The study of temporary or elastic deformation in the case of engineering strain is applied to materials used in mechanical and structural engineering, such as concrete and steel, which are subjected to very small deformations.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Engineering strain is modeled by infinitesimal strain theory, also called *small strain theory*, *small deformation theory*, *small displacement theory*, or *small displacement-gradient theory* where strains and rotations are both small.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Elastomers and shape memory metals such as Nitinol exhibit large elastic deformation ranges, as does rubber.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] However, elasticity is nonlinear in these materials.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Normal metals, ceramics and most crystals show linear elasticity and a smaller elastic range.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] This relationship only applies in the elastic range and indicates that the slope of the stress vs. strain curve can be used to find Young's modulus (E).
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Engineers often use this calculation in tensile tests.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] The area under this elastic region is known as resilience.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Note that not all elastic materials undergo linear elastic deformation; some, such as concrete, gray cast iron, and many polymers, respond in a nonlinear fashion.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] For these materials Hooke's law is inapplicable.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] This type of deformation is not undone simply by removing the applied force.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] An object in the plastic deformation range, however, will first have undergone elastic deformation, which is undone simply by removing the applied force, so the object will return part way to its original shape.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Soft thermoplastics have a rather large plastic deformation range as do ductile metals such as copper, silver, and gold.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Hard thermosetting plastics, rubber, crystals, and ceramics have minimal plastic deformation ranges.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] An example of a material with a large plastic deformation range is wet chewing gum, which can be stretched to dozens of times its original length.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Under tensile stress, plastic deformation is characterized by a strain hardening region and a necking region and finally, fracture (also called rupture).
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] During strain hardening the material becomes stronger through the movement of atomic dislocations.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] The necking phase is indicated by a reduction in cross-sectional area of the specimen.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Necking begins after the ultimate strength is reached.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] During necking, the material can no longer withstand the maximum stress and the strain in the specimen rapidly increases.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Plastic deformation ends with the fracture of the material.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Usually, compressive stress applied to bars, columns, etc. leads to shortening.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Loading a structural element or specimen will increase the compressive stress until it reaches its compressive strength.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] According to the properties of the material, failure modes are yielding for materials with ductile behavior (most metals, some soils and plastics) or rupturing for brittle behavior (geomaterials, cast iron, glass, etc.).
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] In long, slender structural elements — such as columns or truss bars — an increase of compressive force *F* leads to structural failure due to buckling at lower stress than the compressive strength.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] A break occurs after the material has reached the end of the elastic, and then plastic, deformation ranges.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] At this point forces accumulate until they are sufficient to cause a fracture.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] All materials will eventually fracture, if sufficient forces are applied.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Consider a bar of original cross sectional area *A*0 being subjected to equal and opposite forces F pulling at the ends so the bar is under tension.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Subscript 0 denotes the original dimensions of the sample.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] The SI derived unit for stress is newtons per square metre, or pascals (1 pascal = 1 Pa = 1 N/m2), and strain is unitless.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] The stress–strain curve for this material is plotted by elongating the sample and recording the stress variation with strain until the sample fractures.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] By convention, the strain is set to the horizontal axis and stress is set to vertical axis.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Note that for engineering purposes we often assume the cross-section area of the material does not change during the whole deformation process.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] This is not true since the actual area will decrease while deforming due to elastic and plastic deformation.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] The curve based on the original cross-section and gauge length is called the *engineering stress–strain curve*, while the curve based on the instantaneous cross-section area and length is called the *true stress–strain curve*.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Unless stated otherwise, engineering stress–strain is generally used.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Here the dimensions are instantaneous values.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] The true stress and strain can be expressed by engineering stress and strain.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] So in a tension test, true stress is larger than engineering stress and true strain is less than engineering strain.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Thus, a point defining true stress–strain curve is displaced upwards and to the left to define the equivalent engineering stress–strain curve.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] The difference between the true and engineering stresses and strains will increase with plastic deformation.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] At low strains (such as elastic deformation), the differences between the two is negligible.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] As for the tensile strength point, it is the maximal point in engineering stress–strain curve but is not a special point in true stress–strain curve.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] This analysis suggests nature of the ultimate tensile strength (UTS) point.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] The work strengthening effect is exactly balanced by the shrinking of section area at UTS point.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] After the formation of necking, the sample undergoes heterogeneous deformation, so equations above are not valid.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] An empirical equation is commonly used to describe the relationship between true stress and true strain.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Here, n is the strain-hardening exponent and K is the strength coefficient. n is a measure of a material's work hardening behavior.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Materials with a higher n have a greater resistance to necking.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Typically, metals at room temperature have n ranging from 0.02 to 0.5.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Since we disregard the change of area during deformation above, the true stress and strain curve should be re-derived.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] For deriving the stress strain curve, we can assume that the volume change is 0 even if we deformed the materials.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Thus, we can induce the plot in terms of $\sigma _{T}$ and $\varepsilon _{E}$ as right figure.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Additionally, based on the true stress-strain curve, we can estimate the region where necking starts to happen.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] It indicates that the necking starts to appear where reduction of area becomes much significant compared to the stress change.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Then the stress will be localized to specific area where the necking appears.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Additionally, we can induce various relation based on true stress-strain curve.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] 1) True strain and stress curve can be expressed by the approximate linear relationship by taking a log on true stress and strain.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Where K is stress coefficient and n is strain-hardening coefficient.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Usually, the value of n has range around 0.02 to 0.5 at room temperature.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] If n is 1, we can express this material as perfect elastic material.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] 2) In reality, stress is also highly dependent on the rate of strain variation.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Thus, we can induce the empirical equation based on the strain rate variation.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Where $K'$ is constant related to the material flow stress. ${\dot {\varepsilon _{T}}}$ indicates the derivative of strain by the time, which is also known as strain rate. m is the strain-rate sensitivity.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Moreover, value of m is related to the resistance toward the necking.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Usually, the value of m is at the range of 0-0.1 at room temperature and as high as 0.8 when the temperature is increased.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Where $K''$ is the global constant for relating strain, strain rate and stress.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] 3) Based on the true stress-strain curve and its derivative form, we can estimate the strain necessary to start necking.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] This can be calculated based on the intersection between true stress-strain curve as shown in right.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] This figure also shows the dependency of the necking strain at different temperature.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] In case of FCC metals, both of the stress-strain curve at its derivative are highly dependent on temperature.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Therefore, at higher temperature, necking starts to appear even under lower strain value.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] All of these properties indicate the importance of calculating the true stress-strain curve for further analyzing the behavior of materials in sudden environment.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] 4) A graphical method, so-called "Considere construction", can help determine the behavior of stress-strain curve whether necking or drawing happens on the sample.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Therefore, the value of engineering stress can be expressed by the secant line from made by true stress and $\lambda$ value where $\lambda =0$ to $\lambda =1$ .
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] By analyzing the shape of $\sigma _{T}-\lambda$ diagram and secant line, we can determine whether the materials show drawing or necking.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] On the figure (a), there is only concave upward Considere plot.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] It indicates that there is no yield drop so the material will be suffered from fracture before it yields.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] On the figure (b), there is specific point where the tangent matches with secant line at point where $\lambda =\lambda _{Y}$ .
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] After this value, the slope becomes smaller than the secant line where necking starts to appear.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] On the figure (c), there is point where yielding starts to appear but when $\lambda =\lambda _{d}$ , the drawing happens.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] After drawing, all the material will stretch and eventually show fracture.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] Between $\lambda _{Y}$ and $\lambda _{d}$ , the material itself does not stretch but rather, only the neck starts to stretch out.
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] A popular misconception is that all materials that bend are "weak" and those that do not are "strong".
[src:load-cells-strain/deformation-engineering] In reality, many materials that undergo large elastic and plastic deformations, such as steel, are able to absorb stresses that would cause brittle materials, such as glass, with minimal plastic deformation ranges, to break.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] A **force-sensing resistor** is a material whose resistance changes when a force, pressure or mechanical stress is applied.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] They are also known as **force-sensitive resistor** and are sometimes referred to by the initialism **FSR**.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] The technology of force-sensing resistors was invented and patented in 1977 by Franklin Eventoff.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] In 1985, Eventoff founded Interlink Electronics, a company based on his force-sensing-resistor (FSR).
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] In 1987, Eventoff received the prestigious International IR 100 award for developing the FSR.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] In 2001, Eventoff founded a new company, Sensitronics, that he currently runs.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Force-sensing resistors consist of a conductive polymer, which predictably changes resistance following applying force to its surface.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] They are normally supplied as a polymer sheet or ink that can be applied by screen printing.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] The sensing film consists of electrically conducting and non-conducting particles suspended in a matrix.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] The particles are sub-micrometre sizes formulated to reduce temperature dependence, improve mechanical properties and increase surface durability.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Applying a force to the surface of the sensing film causes particles to touch the conducting electrodes, changing the film's resistance.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] As with all resistive-based sensors, force-sensing resistors require a relatively simple interface and can operate satisfactorily in moderately hostile environments.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Compared to other force sensors, the advantages of FSRs are their size (thickness typically less than 0.5 mm), low cost, and good shock resistance.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] A disadvantage is their low precision: measurement results may differ by 10% and more.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Force-sensing capacitors offer superior sensitivity and long-term stability, but require more complicated drive electronics.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] There are two major operation principles in force-sensing resistors: percolation and quantum tunneling.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Although both phenomena co-occur in the conductive polymer, one phenomenon dominates over the other depending on particle concentration.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Particle concentration is also referred in the literature as the filler volume fraction $\phi$ .
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] More recently, new mechanistic explanations have been established to explain the performance of force-sensing resistors; these are based on the property of contact resistance $R_{C}$ occurring between the sensor electrodes and the conductive polymer.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Specifically the force induced transition from Sharvin contacts to conventional Holm contacts.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] The contact resistance, $R_{C}$ , plays an important role in the current conduction of force-sensing resistors in a twofold manner.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] First, for a given applied stress $\sigma$ , or force F , a plastic deformation occurs between the sensor electrodes and the polymer particles thus reducing the contact resistance.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Second, the uneven polymer surface is flattened when subjected to incremental forces, and therefore, more contact paths are created; this causes an increment in the effective area for current conduction A .
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] At a macroscopic scale, the polymer surface is smooth.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] However, under a scanning electron microscope, the conductive polymer is irregular due to agglomerations of the polymeric binder.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] To date, no comprehensive model is capable of predicting all the non-linearities observed in force-sensing resistors.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] The multiple phenomena occurring in the conductive polymer turn out to be too complex such to embrace them all simultaneously; this condition is typical of systems encompassed within condensed matter physics.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] However, in most cases, the experimental behavior of force-sensing resistors can be grossly approximated to either the percolation theory or to the equations governing quantum tunneling through a rectangular potential barrier.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] The percolation phenomenon dominates in the conductive polymer when the particle concentration is above the percolation threshold $\phi _{c}$ .
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] where $\rho _{0}$ matches for a prefactor depending on the transport properties of the conductive polymer, and x is the critical conductivity exponent.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Under percolation regime, the particles are separated from each other when mechanical stress is applied; this causes a net increment in the device's resistance.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Quantum tunneling is the most common operation mode of force-sensing resistors.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] A conductive polymer operating on the basis of quantum tunneling exhibits a resistance decrement for incremental values of stress $\sigma$ .
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Commercial FSRs such as the FlexiForce, Interlink and Peratech sensors operate based on quantum tunneling.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] The Peratech sensors are also referred to in the literature as quantum tunnelling composite.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Similarly, the contact resistance $R_{C}$ is reduced amid larger applied forces.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] To operate based on quantum tunneling, particle concentration in the conductive polymer must be held below the percolation threshold $\phi _{c}$ .
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Several authors have developed theoretical models for the quantum tunneling conduction of FSRs, some of the models rely upon the equations for particle transmission across a rectangular potential barrier.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] However, the practical usage of such equations is limited because they are stated in terms of electron energy, E , that follows a Fermi Dirac probability distribution, i.e., electron energy is not a priori determined or can not be set by the final user.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] The analytical derivation of the equations for a rectangular potential barrier including the Fermi Dirac distribution was found in the 60's by Simmons.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Such equations relate the current density J with the external applied voltage across the sensor U .
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] However, J is not straightforward measurable in practice, so the transformation $I=JA$ is usually applied in literature when dealing with FSRs.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Just as in the equations for a rectangular potential barrier, the Simmons' equations are piecewise regarding the magnitude of U , i.e., different expressions are stated depending on U and the height of the rectangular potential barrier $V_{a}$ .
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] where $V_{a}$ is in units of electron volt, m , e are the electron's mass and charge respectively, and h is the Planck constant.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] The low voltage equation of the Simmons' model is fundamental for modeling the current conduction of FSRs.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] The most widely accepted model for tunneling conduction has been proposed by Zhang et al. based on such equation.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] where M is the Young's modulus of the conductive polymer.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Although the model from Zhang et al. has been widely accepted by many authors, it has been unable to predict some experimental observations reported in force-sensing resistors.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Probably, the most challenging phenomenon to predict is sensitivity degradation.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] When subjected to dynamic loading, some force-sensing resistors exhibit degradation in sensitivity.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] where $R_{par}$ is the resistance of the conductive nano-particles and $R_{C}^{0}$ , k are experimentally determined factors that depend on the interface material between the conductive polymer and the electrode.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] In the equations above, the effective area for tunneling conduction A is stated as an increasing function dependent on the applied stress $\sigma$ , and on coefficients $A_{0}$ , $A_{1}$ , $A_{2}$ to be experimentally determined.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Although the above model is unable to describe the undesired phenomenon of sensitivity degradation, the inclusion of rheological models has predicted that drift can be reduced by choosing an appropriate sourcing voltage; experimental observations have supported this statement.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Another approach to reduce drift is to employ non-aligned electrodes to minimize the effects of polymer creep.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] Force-sensing resistors are commonly used to create pressure-sensing "buttons" and have applications in many fields, including musical instruments (such as the Sensel Morph), car occupancy sensors, artificial limbs, foot pronation systems, and portable electronics.
[src:load-cells-strain/force-sensing-resistor] They are also used in mixed or augmented reality systems as well as to enhance mobile interaction.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] A **load cell** converts a force such as tension, compression, pressure, or torque into a signal (electrical, pneumatic or hydraulic pressure, or mechanical displacement indicator) that can be measured and standardized.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] As the force applied to the load cell increases, the signal changes proportionally.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The most common types of load cells are pneumatic, hydraulic, and strain gauge types for industrial applications.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Typical non-electronic bathroom scales are a widespread example of a mechanical displacement indicator where the applied weight (force) is indicated by measuring the deflection of springs supporting the load platform, technically a "load cell".
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Strain gauge load cells are the kind most often found in industrial settings.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] It is ideal as it is highly accurate, versatile, and cost-effective.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Structurally, a load cell has a metal body to which strain gauges have been secured.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The body is usually made of aluminum, alloy steel, or stainless steel which makes it very sturdy but also minimally elastic.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] This elasticity gives rise to the term "spring element", referring to the body of the load cell.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] When force is exerted on the load cell, the spring element is slightly deformed, and unless overloaded, always returns to its original shape.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] As the spring element deforms, the strain gauges also change shape.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The resulting alteration to the resistance in the strain gauges can be measured as voltage.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The change in voltage is proportional to the amount of force applied to the cell, so the amount of force can be calculated from the load cell's output.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] A strain gauge is constructed of very fine wire, or foil, set up in a grid pattern and attached to a flexible backing.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] When the shape of the strain gauge is altered, a change in its electrical resistance occurs.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The wire or foil in the strain gauge is arranged in a way that, when force is applied in one direction, a linear change in resistance results.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Tension force stretches a strain gauge, causing it to get thinner and longer, resulting in an increase in resistance.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The strain gauge compresses, becomes thicker and shorter, and resistance decreases.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The strain gauge is attached to a flexible backing enabling it to be easily applied to a load cell, mirroring the minute changes to be measured.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Since the change in resistance measured by a single strain gauge is extremely small, it is difficult to accurately measure changes.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Increasing the number of strain gauges applied collectively magnifies these small changes into something more measurable.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] A set of 4 strain gauges set in a specific circuit is an application of a Wheatstone bridge.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] A Wheatstone bridge is a configuration of four balanced resistors with a known excitation voltage applied.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Excitation voltage $V_{\text{EX}}$ is a known constant, and output voltage $V_{\text{o}}$ is variable depending on the shape of the strain gauges.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] If all resistors are balanced, meaning $R1/R2=R4/R3$ , then $V_{\text{o}}$ is zero.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] If the resistance in even one of the resistors changes, then $V_{\text{o}}$ likewise changes.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The change in $V_{\text{o}}$ can be measured and interpreted using Ohm's law.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Ohm's law states that the current ( I , measured in amperes) running through a conductor between two points is directly proportional to the voltage V across the two points.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Resistance ( R , measured in ohms) is introduced as the constant in this relationship, independent of the current.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Ohm's law is expressed in the equation $I=V/R$ .
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] In a load cell, the resistors are replaced with strain gauges and arranged in alternating tension and compression formation.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] When force is exerted on the load cell, the structure and resistance of the strain gauges changes, and $V_{\text{o}}$ is measured.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] From the resulting data, $V_{\text{o}}$ can be easily determined using the equation above.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The digital capacitive technology is based on a non-contacting ceramic sensor mounted inside the load cell body.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] As the load cell contains no moving parts and the ceramic sensor is not in contact with the load cell body, the load cell tolerates very high overloads (up to 1000%), sideloads, torsion, and stray welding voltages.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] This allows for simple installation of the load cells without expensive and complicated mounting kits, stay rods, or overload protection devices, which in turn eliminates the need for maintenance.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Capacitive and strain gauge load cells both rely on an elastic element that is deformed by the load to be measured.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The material used for the elastic element is normally aluminum or stainless steel for load cells used in corrosive industrial applications.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] A strain gauge sensor measures the deformation of the elastic element, and the output of the sensor is converted by an electronic circuit to a signal that represents the load.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Capacitive strain gauges measure the deformation of the elastic material using the change in capacitance of two plates as the plates move closer to each other.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Capacitive sensors have a high sensitivity compared to strain gauges.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Because of the much higher sensitivity, a much lower deformation of the elastic element is needed, and the elastic element of a capacitive load cell is therefore strained around 5 to 10 times lower than the elastic element of a strain gauge load cell.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The low strained element combined with the fact that a capacitive sensor is non-contacting, provides the very high shock resistance and overload capability of the capacitive load cell compared to the strain gage load cell.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] This is an obvious advantage in industrial environments and especially for the lower capacity load cells where the risk of damage because of shocks and overloads is high.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] In a standard analog strain gauge load cell, the power supply and the low-level analog signal are normally conducted through a rather expensive 6-wire cable to the instrumentation where the analog signal is converted to a digital signal.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Instead, digital capacitive load cells transmit the digital signal back to the instrumentation which may be placed several hundred meters away without influencing the reading.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The pneumatic load cell is designed to automatically regulate the balancing pressure.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Air pressure is applied to one end of the diaphragm and it escapes through the nozzle placed at the bottom of the load cell.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] A pressure gauge is attached to the load cell to measure the pressure inside the cell.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The deflection of the diaphragm affects the airflow through the nozzle as well as the pressure inside the chamber.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The hydraulic load cell uses a conventional piston and cylinder arrangement with the piston placed in a thin elastic diaphragm.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The piston doesn't actually come in contact with the load cell.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Mechanical stops are placed to prevent overstrain of the diaphragm when the loads exceed a certain limit.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The load cell is completely filled with oil.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] When the load is applied on the piston, the movement of the piston and the diaphragm results in an increase of oil pressure.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] This pressure is then transmitted to a hydraulic pressure gauge via a high pressure hose.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The gauge's Bourdon tube senses the pressure and registers it on the dial.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Because this sensor has no electrical components, it is ideal for use in hazardous areas.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Typical hydraulic load cell applications include tank, bin, and hopper weighing.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] By example, a hydraulic load cell is immune to transient voltages (lightning) so these types of load cells might be a more effective device in outdoor environments.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] This technology is more expensive than other types of load cells.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] It is a more costly technology and thus cannot effectively compete on a cost of purchase basis.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Piezoelectric load cells work on the same principle of deformation as the strain gauge load cells, but a voltage output is generated by the basic piezoelectric material – proportional to the deformation of load cell.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Useful for dynamic/frequent measurements of force.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Most applications for piezo-based load cells are in the dynamic loading conditions, where strain gauge load cells can fail with high dynamic loading cycles.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The piezoelectric effect is dynamic, that is, the electrical output of a gauge is an impulse function and is not static.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The voltage output is only useful when the strain is changing and does not measure static values.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] However, depending on conditioning system used, "quasi static" operation can be done.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Using a charge amplifier with a long time constant allows accurate measurement lasting many minutes for small loads up to many hours for large loads.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Another advantage of Piezoelectric load cells conditioned with a charge amplifier is the wide measuring range that can be achieved.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Users can choose a load cell with a range of hundred of kilonewtons and use it for measuring few newtons of force with the same signal-to-noise ratio; again this is possible only with the use of a charge amplifier for conditioning.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The bridge is excited with stabilized voltage (usually 10V, but can be 20V, 5V, or less for battery powered instrumentation).
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The difference voltage proportional to the load then appears on the signal outputs.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The cell output is rated in millivolts per volt (mV/V) of the difference voltage at full rated mechanical load.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] So a 2.96 mV/V load cell will provide 29.6 millivolt signal at full load when excited with 10 volts.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Typical sensitivity values are 1 to 3 mV/V.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Typical maximum excitation voltage is around 15 volts.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The full-bridge cells come typically in four-wire configuration.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The wires to the top and bottom end of the bridge are the excitation (often labelled E+ and E−, or Ex+ and Ex−), the wires to its sides are the signal (labelled S+ and S−).
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Ideally, the voltage difference between S+ and S− is zero under zero load, and grows proportionally to the load cell's mechanical load.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Sometimes a six-wire configuration is used.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The two additional wires are "sense" (Sen+ and Sen−), and are connected to the bridge with the Ex+ and Ex- wires, in a fashion similar to four-terminal sensing.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] With these additional signals, the controller can compensate for the change in wire resistance due to external factors, e.g. temperature fluctuations.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The individual resistors on the bridge usually have resistance of 350 Ω.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Sometimes other values (typically 120 Ω, 1,000 Ω) can be encountered.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The bridge is typically electrically insulated from the substrate.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The sensing elements are in close proximity and in good mutual thermal contact, to avoid differential signals caused by temperature differences.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] One or more load cells can be used for sensing a single load.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] If the force can be concentrated to a single point (small scale sensing, ropes, tensile loads, point loads), a single cell can be used.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] For long beams, two cells at the end are used.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Vertical cylinders can be measured at three points, rectangular objects usually require four sensors.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] More sensors are used for large containers or platforms, or very high loads.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] If the loads are guaranteed to be symmetrical, some of the load cells can be substituted with pivots.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] This saves the cost of the load cell but can significantly decrease accuracy.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Load cells can be connected in parallel; in that case, all the corresponding signals are connected together (Ex+ to Ex+, S+ to S+, ...), and the resulting signal is the average of the signals from all the sensing elements.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] This is often used in e.g. personal scales, or other multipoint weight sensors.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The most common color assignment is red for Ex+, black for Ex−, green for S+, and white for S−.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Less common assignments are red for Ex+, white for Ex−, green for S+, and blue for S−, or red for Ex+, blue for Ex−, green for S+, and yellow for S−.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Other values are also possible, e.g. red for Ex+, green for Ex−, yellow for S+ and blue for S−.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Every load cell is subject to "ringing" when subjected to abrupt load changes.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] This stems from the spring-like behavior of load cells.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] In order to measure the loads, they have to deform.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] As such, a load cell of finite stiffness must have spring-like behavior, exhibiting vibrations at its natural frequency.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] An oscillating data pattern can be the result of ringing.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Ringing can be suppressed in a limited fashion by passive means.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Alternatively, a control system can use an actuator to actively damp out the ringing of a load cell.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] This method offers better performance at a cost of significant increase in complexity.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Load cells are used in several types of measuring instruments such as laboratory balances, industrial scales, platform scales and universal testing machines.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] From 1993 the British Antarctic Survey installed load cells in glass fibre nests to weigh albatross chicks.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Load cells are used in a wide variety of items such as the seven-post shaker which is often used to set up race cars.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Another common use is within sim racing, where the advantage of a load cell over a potentiometer is that simulated braking force is based on the user’s force on the pedal, rather than the position of the pedal.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Load cells are also widely used in food processing, warehousing, logistics, and general manufacturing for applications such as batching, filling, pallet weighing, shipping verification, and process monitoring.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Load cells are commonly used to measure weight in an industrial environment.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] They can be installed on hoppers, reactors, etc., to control their weight capacity, which is often of critical importance for an industrial process.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Some performance characteristics of the load cells must be defined and specified to make sure they will cope with the expected service.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] The electrical, physical, and environmental specifications of a load cell help to determine which applications it is appropriate for.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Load cells are an integral part of most weighing systems in industrial, aerospace and automotive industries, enduring rigorous daily use.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Over time, load cells will drift, age and misalign; therefore, they will need to be calibrated regularly to ensure accurate results are maintained.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] ISO9000 and most other standards specify a maximum period of around 18 months to 2 years between re-calibration procedures, dependent on the level of load cell deterioration.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Annual re-calibration is considered best practice by many load cell users for ensuring the most accurate measurements.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Standard calibration tests will use linearity and repeatability as a calibration guideline as these are both used to determine accuracy.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Calibration is conducted incrementally starting working in ascending or descending order.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] For example, in the case of a 60 tonne load cell, then specific test weights that measure in 5, 10, 20, 40 and 60 tonne increments may be used; a five step calibration process is usually sufficient for ensuring a device is accurately calibrated.
[src:load-cells-strain/load-cell] Repeating this five-step calibration procedure 2-3 times is recommended for consistent results.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] A **strain gauge** (also spelled **strain gage**) is a device used to measure strain on an object.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Ruge in 1938, the most common type of strain gauge consists of an insulating flexible backing which supports a metallic foil pattern.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The gauge is attached to the object by a suitable adhesive, such as cyanoacrylate.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Proper adhesion is critical, as any air gaps or flexibility in the bonding layer will introduce measurement errors known as creep or hysteresis.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] As the object is deformed, the foil is deformed, causing its electrical resistance to change.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] This resistance change, usually measured using a Wheatstone bridge, is related to the strain by the quantity known as the gauge factor.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Ruge independently invented the strain gauge.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Simmons was involved in a research project by Dätwyler and Clark at Caltech between 1936 and 1938.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] They researched the stress-strain behavior of metals under shock loads.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Simmons came up with an original way to measure the force introduced into the sample by equipping a dynamometer with fine resistance wires.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Ruge, a professor at MIT, on the other hand, conducted research in seismology.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] He tried to analyze the behavior of a model water tank installed on a vibration table.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] He was not able to utilize the standard optical strain measurement methods of his time due to the small scale and low strains in his model.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Hanns Meier) had the epiphany of measuring the resistance change caused by strain in metallic wires cemented on the thin walls of the water tank model.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The development of the strain gauge was essentially just a byproduct of other research projects.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Ruge developed a widely used and useful measurement tool due to the lack of an alternative at their times.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Ruge realized the commercial utility of the strain gauge.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] His employer at MIT waived all claims on the right of the invention, as they did not predict the economic and large-scale usage potential.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The strain gauge applications were quickly gaining traction as they served to indirectly detect all other quantities that induce strain.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Additionally, they were simple to install by the scientists, did not cause any obstruction or property changes to the observed object and thus falsifying the measurement results.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Probably the last and most important property was the ease of transmission of the electrical output signal.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] A strain gauge takes advantage of the physical property of electrical conductance and its dependence on the conductor's geometry.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] When an electrical conductor is stretched within the limits of its elasticity such that it does not break or permanently deform, it will become narrower and longer, which increases its electrical resistance end-to-end.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Conversely, when a conductor is compressed such that it does not buckle, it will broaden and shorten, which decreases its electrical resistance end-to-end.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] From the measured electrical resistance of the strain gauge, the amount of induced stress may be inferred.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] A typical strain gauge arranges a long, thin conductive strip in a zig-zag pattern of parallel lines.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] This does not increase the sensitivity, since the percentage change in resistance for a given strain for the entire zig-zag is the same as for any single trace.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] A single linear trace would have to be extremely thin, hence liable to overheating (which would change its resistance and cause it to expand), or would need to be operated at a much lower voltage, making it difficult to measure resistance changes accurately.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] For common metallic foil gauges, the gauge factor is usually a little over 2.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Foil gauges typically have active areas of about 2–10 mm2 in size.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] With careful installation, the correct gauge, and the correct adhesive, strains up to at least 10% can be measured.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] An excitation voltage is applied to input leads of the gauge network, and a voltage reading is taken from the output leads.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Typical input voltages are 5 V or 12 V and typical output readings are in millivolts.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Foil strain gauges are used in many situations.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Different applications place different requirements on the gauge.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] In most cases the orientation of the strain gauge is significant.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Strain gauges are attached to the substrate with a special glue.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The type of glue depends on the required lifetime of the measurement system.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] For short term measurements (up to some weeks) cyanoacrylate glue is appropriate, for long lasting installation epoxy glue is required.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Usually epoxy glue requires high temperature curing (at about 80-100 °C).
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The preparation of the surface where the strain gauge is to be glued is of the utmost importance.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The surface must be smoothed (e.g. with very fine sand paper), deoiled with solvents, the solvent traces must then be removed and the strain gauge must be glued immediately after this to avoid oxidation or pollution of the prepared area.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] If these steps are not followed the strain gauge binding to the surface may be unreliable and unpredictable measurement errors may be generated.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Strain gauge based technology is used commonly in the manufacture of pressure sensors.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The gauges used in pressure sensors themselves are commonly made from silicon, polysilicon, metal film, thick film, and bonded foil.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Variations in temperature will cause a multitude of effects.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The object will change in size by thermal expansion, which will be detected as a strain by the gauge.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Resistance of the gauge will change, and resistance of the connecting wires will change.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Most strain gauges are made from a constantan alloy.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Various constantan alloys and Karma alloys have been designed so that the temperature effects on the resistance of the strain gauge itself largely cancel out the resistance change of the gauge due to the thermal expansion of the object under test.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Because different materials have different amounts of thermal expansion, self-temperature compensation (STC) requires selecting a particular alloy matched to the material of the object under test.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Strain gauges that are not self-temperature-compensated (such as isoelastic alloy) can be temperature compensated by use of the dummy gauge technique.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] A dummy gauge (identical to the active strain gauge) is installed on an unstrained sample of the same material as the test specimen.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The sample with the dummy gauge is placed in thermal contact with the test specimen, adjacent to the active gauge.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The dummy gauge is wired into a Wheatstone bridge on an adjacent arm to the active gauge so that the temperature effects on the active and dummy gauges cancel each other.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Every material reacts when it heats up or when it cools down.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] This will cause strain gauges to register a deformation in the material which will make it change signal.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] To prevent this from happening strain gauges are made so they will compensate this change due to temperature.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Dependent on the material of the surface where the strain gauge is assembled on, a different expansion can be measured.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Temperature effects on the lead wires can be cancelled by using a "3-wire bridge" or a "4-wire ohm circuit" (also called a "4-wire Kelvin connection").
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] In any case it is a good engineering practice to keep the Wheatstone bridge voltage drive low enough to avoid the self heating of the strain gauge.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The self heating of the strain gauge depends on its mechanical characteristic (large strain gauges are less prone to self heating).
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Low voltage drive levels of the bridge reduce the sensitivity of the overall system.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Structural health monitoring (SHM) is used to monitor structures after their completion.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] To prevent failures, strain gauges are used to detect and locate damages and creep.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] A specific example is the monitoring of bridge cables increasing safety by detecting possible damages.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Also, the bridge's behavior to unusual loads such as special heavy-duty transports can be analyzed.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Measuring the strain of skin can provide a multitude of biomechanic measurements such as posture, joint rotation, respiration and swelling both in humans and other animals.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Resistive foil strain gauges are seldom used for these applications, however, due to their low strain limit.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Instead, soft and deformable strain gauges are often attached to a host garment, to make it simple to apply the sensor to the correct part of the body, though sometimes they are attached directly to the skin.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Typically in these applications, such soft strain gauges are known as stretch sensors.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] For medical use, the sensors must be accurate and repeatable which typically requires the use of capacitive stretch sensors.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Many objects and materials in industrial applications have a finite life.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] To improve their lifetime and cost of ownership, predictive maintenance principles are used.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Strain gauges can be used to monitor the strain as an indicator of fatigue in materials to enable software systems to predict when certain components need to be replaced or serviced.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Resistive foil gauges can be used to instrument stiff materials like metals, ceramics, composites and similar, whereas highly elastic strain gauges are used to monitor softer materials such as rubber, plastics, textiles and the like.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] In aviation, strain gauges are the standard approach to measuring the structural load and calculating wing deflection.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Strain gauges are fixed in several locations on the aircraft.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] However, deflection measurement systems have been shown to measure strains reliably remotely.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] This reduces instrumentation weight on the aircraft and thus is replacing (certain) strain gauges.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] There are also applications where it isn't first obvious that you would measure strain to get to the wanted result.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] So for example in the detection of intruders on certain structures, strain gauges can be used to detect the presence of such an intruder.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] This is done by measuring the slight change in strain of the said structure.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] In some applications, strain gauges add mass and damping to the vibration profiles of the hardware they are intended to measure.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] In the turbomachinery industry, one used alternative to strain gauge technology in the measurement of vibrations on rotating hardware is the non-intrusive stress measurement system, which allows measurement of blade vibrations without any blade or disc-mounted hardware.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Strain Gauge measurement devices are prone to drift problems.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Additionally, their manufacturing requires precise requirements during all the production steps.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] So there are multiple different ways of also measuring strain.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Strain can also be measured using digital image correlation (DIC).
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] With this technique one or two cameras are used in conjunction with a DIC software to track features on the surface of components to detect small motion.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The full strain map of the tested sample can be calculated, providing similar display as a finite-element analysis.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] This technique is used in many industries to replace traditional strain gauges or other sensors like extensometers, string pots, LVDT, accelerometers.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The accuracy of commercially available DIC software typically ranges around 1/100 to 1/30 of a pixel for displacement measurements which result in strain sensitivity between 20 and 100 parts per million.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The DIC technique allows to quickly measure shape, displacements and strain non-contact, avoiding some issues of traditional contacting methods, especially with impacts, high-strain, high-temperature or high-cycle fatigue testing.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Stefan Keil published the first edition of a detailed book about strain gauges and how to use them called *Dehnungsmessstreifen*.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Although this first edition was only published in German, it became popular outside of Germany because of the wide range of uses of strain gauges in different fields.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] After more than 20 years (in 2017), he published a second edition that was translated into English, hence available to more engineers that use strain gauges.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] This newest book is titled *Technology and Practical Use of Strain Gages*.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The term *strain gauge* can be encountered in sociology.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The social strain gauge theory is an approach to understanding accusations of witchcraft and sorcery.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] South African anthropologist Maxwell Marwick studied these sociological phenomena in Zambia and Malawi in 1965.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] Accusations of witchcraft reflect strain on relationships or a whole social structure.
[src:load-cells-strain/strain-gauge] The theory says that the sorcery accusations were a pressure valve of society.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] In physics and mechanics, **torque** is the rotational correspondent of linear force.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] It is also referred to as the **moment of force**, or simply the **moment**.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Just as a linear force is a push or a pull applied to a body, a torque can be thought of as a twist applied to an object with respect to a chosen axis.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] For example, when driving a screw, a screwdriver applies torque to the screw, causing it to tend to rotate around its axis.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Torque is generally referred to using different vocabulary depending on geographical location and field of study, with *torque* generally being associated with physics and *moment* being associated with engineering.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] This article follows the definition used in US physics in its usage of the word *torque*.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Torque is typically represented mathematically using the lowercase Greek letter *tau* (𝜏).
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] When being referred to as moment of force, it is commonly denoted by M.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The term *torque* (from Latin *torquēre*, 'to twist') is said to have been suggested by James Thomson and appeared in print in April, 1884.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Usage is attested the same year by Silvanus P.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Thompson in the first edition of *Dynamo-Electric Machinery*.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] In mechanical engineering in the UK and the US, torque is generally referred to as *moment of force*, usually shortened to *moment*.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] This terminology can be traced back to at least 1811 in Siméon Denis Poisson's *Traité de mécanique*.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] An English translation of Poisson's work appeared in 1842.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The torque about an axis can be calculated by multiplying the linear force applied perpendicularly to a lever multiplied by its distance from the lever's fulcrum (the length of the **lever arm**).
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Therefore, torque is defined as the product of the magnitude of the perpendicular component of the force and the distance of the line of action of a force from the point around which it is being determined.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] In three dimensions, the torque is a pseudovector; for point particles, it is given by the cross product of the displacement vector and the force vector.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The direction of the torque can be determined by using the right-hand grip rule: if the fingers of the right hand are curled from the direction of the lever arm to the direction of the force, then the thumb points in the direction of the torque.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] It follows that the **torque vector** is perpendicular to both the *position* and *force* vectors, and defines the plane in which the two vectors lie.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The resulting torque vector direction is determined by the right-hand rule.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Therefore any force directed parallel to the particle's position vector does not produce a torque.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The magnitude of torque applied to a rigid body depends on three quantities: the force applied, the **lever arm vector** connecting the point about which the torque is being measured to the point of force application, and the angle between the force and lever arm vectors.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The SI unit for torque is the newton-meter (N⋅m).
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] For more on the units of torque, see *§ Units*.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] where ${\textstyle \mathbf {L} }$ is the angular momentum vector and ${\textstyle t}$ is time.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] where ${\textstyle I=mr^{2}}$ is the moment of inertia and ${\textstyle {\boldsymbol {\omega }}}$ is the orbital angular velocity pseudovector.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] using the derivative of a vector is ${\mathrm {d} {\hat {\boldsymbol {e}}}_{\text{i}} \over \mathrm {d} t}={\boldsymbol {\omega }}\times {\hat {\boldsymbol {e}}}_{\text{i}}$ This equation is the rotational analogue of Newton's second law for point particles, and is valid for any type of trajectory.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] In some simple cases like a rotating disc, where only the moment of inertia on rotating axis is, the rotational Newton's second law can be ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}=I{\boldsymbol {\alpha }}$ where ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}={\dot {\boldsymbol {\omega }}}$ .
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The definition of angular momentum for a single point particle is: $\mathbf {L} =\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {p}$ where **p** is the particle's linear momentum and **r** is the position vector from the origin.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] This result can easily be proven by splitting the vectors into components and applying the product rule.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The cross product of momentum $\mathbf {p}$ with its associated velocity $\mathbf {v}$ is zero because velocity and momentum are parallel, so the second term vanishes.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Therefore, torque on a particle is *equal* to the first derivative of its angular momentum with respect to time.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] This is a general proof for point particles, but it can be generalized to a system of point particles by applying the above proof to each of the point particles and then summing over all the point particles.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Similarly, the proof can be generalized to a continuous mass by applying the above proof to each point within the mass, and then integrating over the entire mass.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] This word is derived from the Latin word *rotātus* meaning 'to rotate'.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The term *rotatum* is not universally recognized but is commonly used.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] There is not a universally accepted lexicon to indicate the successive derivatives of rotatum, even if sometimes various proposals have been made.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The law of conservation of energy can also be used to understand torque.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] If a force is allowed to act through a distance, it is doing mechanical work.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Similarly, if torque is allowed to act through an angular displacement, it is doing work.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] where *τ* is torque, and *θ*1 and *θ*2 represent (respectively) the initial and final angular positions of the body.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] where *I* is the moment of inertia of the body and *ω* is its angular speed.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] where *P* is power, ***τ*** is torque, ***ω*** is the angular velocity, and $\cdot$ represents the scalar product.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Algebraically, the equation may be rearranged to compute torque for a given angular speed and power output.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Official SI literature indicates the **newton-meter** as the standard unit for torque, properly denoted using N⋅m; although this is dimensionally equivalent to the joule, which is not used for torque.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] In the case of torque, the unit is assigned to a vector, whereas for energy, it is assigned to a scalar.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] This means that the dimensional equivalence of the newton-metre and the joule may be applied in the former but not in the latter case.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] This problem is addressed in orientational analysis, which treats the radian as a base unit rather than as a dimensionless unit.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Torque has the dimension of force times distance, symbolically T−2L2M, and those fundamental dimensions are the same as that for energy or work.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The traditional imperial units for torque are the pound foot (lbf-ft), or, for small values, the pound inch (lbf-in).
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] In the US, torque is most commonly referred to as the **foot-pound** (denoted as either lb-ft or ft-lb) and the **inch-pound** (denoted as in-lb).
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Practitioners depend on context and the hyphen in the abbreviation to know that these refer to torque and not to energy or moment of mass (as the symbolism ft-lb would properly imply).
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] A conversion factor may be necessary when using different units of power or torque.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] For example, if rotational speed (unit: revolution per minute or second) is used in place of angular speed (unit: radian per second), we must multiply by 2π radians per revolution.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] In the following formulas, *P* is power, *τ* is torque, and *ν* (Greek letter nu) is rotational speed.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Dividing by 60 seconds per minute gives us the following.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] where rotational speed is in revolutions per minute (rpm, rev/min).
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Some people (e.g., American automotive engineers) use horsepower (mechanical) for power, foot-pounds (lbf⋅ft) for torque and rpm for rotational speed.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The constant below (in foot-pounds per minute) changes with the definition of the horsepower; for example, using metric horsepower, it becomes approximately 32,550.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The use of other units (e.g., BTU per hour for power) would require a different custom conversion factor.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] For a rotating object, the *linear distance* covered at the circumference of rotation is the product of the radius with the angle covered.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] That is: linear distance = radius × angular distance.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] And by definition, linear distance = linear speed × time = radius × angular speed × time.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] By the definition of torque: torque = radius × force.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] We can rearrange this to determine force = torque ÷ radius.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The radius *r* and time *t* have dropped out of the equation.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] However, angular speed must be in radians per unit of time, by the assumed direct relationship between linear speed and angular speed at the beginning of the derivation.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] If torque is in newton-metres and rotational speed in revolutions per second, the above equation gives power in newton-metres per second or watts.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] If Imperial units are used, and if torque is in pounds-force feet and rotational speed in revolutions per minute, the above equation gives power in foot pounds-force per minute.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The construction of the "moment arm" is shown in the figure to the right, along with the vectors **r** and **F** mentioned above.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The problem with this definition is that it does not give the direction of the torque but only the magnitude, and hence it is difficult to use in three-dimensional cases.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] If the force is perpendicular to the displacement vector **r**, the moment arm will be equal to the distance to the centre, and torque will be a maximum for the given force.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] For an object to be in static equilibrium, not only must the sum of the forces be zero, but also the sum of the torques (moments) about any point.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] For a two-dimensional situation with horizontal and vertical forces, the sum of the forces requirement is two equations: Σ*H* = 0 and Σ*V* = 0, and the torque a third equation: Σ*τ* = 0.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] That is, to solve statically determinate equilibrium problems in two-dimensions, three equations are used.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] When the net force on the system is zero, the torque measured from any point in space is the same.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] For example, the torque on a current-carrying loop in a uniform magnetic field is the same regardless of the point of reference.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Torque forms part of the basic specification of an engine: the power output of an engine is expressed as its torque multiplied by the angular speed of the drive shaft.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Internal-combustion engines produce useful torque only over a limited range of rotational speeds (typically from around 1,000–6,000 rpm for a small car).
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] One can measure the varying torque output over that range with a dynamometer, and show it as a torque curve.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Steam engines and electric motors tend to produce maximum torque close to zero rpm, with the torque diminishing as rotational speed rises (due to increasing friction and other constraints).
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Reciprocating steam-engines and electric motors can start heavy loads from zero rpm without a clutch.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] A cyclist, the person who rides the bicycle, provides the input power by turning pedals, thereby cranking the front sprocket (commonly referred to as chainring).
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The input power provided by the cyclist is equal to the product of angular speed (i.e. the number of pedal revolutions per minute times 2*π*) and the torque at the spindle of the bicycle's crankset.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] The bicycle's drivetrain transmits the input power to the road wheel, which in turn conveys the received power to the road as the output power of the bicycle.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Depending on the gear ratio of the bicycle, a (torque, angular speed)input pair is converted to a (torque, angular speed)output pair.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] By using a larger rear gear, or by switching to a lower gear in multi-speed bicycles, angular speed of the road wheels is decreased while the torque is increased, product of which (i.e. power) does not change.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Torque can be multiplied via three methods: by locating the fulcrum such that the length of a lever is increased; by using a longer lever; or by the use of a speed-reducing gearset or gear box.
[src:load-cells-strain/torque] Such a mechanism multiplies torque, as rotation rate is reduced.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] A **Wheatstone bridge** is an electrical circuit used to measure an unknown electrical resistance by balancing two legs of a bridge circuit, one leg of which includes the unknown component.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] The primary benefit of the circuit is its ability to provide extremely accurate measurements (in contrast with something like a simple voltage divider).
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] Its operation is similar to the original potentiometer.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] The Wheatstone bridge was invented by Samuel Hunter Christie (sometimes spelled "Christy") in 1833 and improved and popularized by Sir Charles Wheatstone in 1843.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] One of the Wheatstone bridge's initial uses was for soil analysis and comparison.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] In the figure, *Rx* is the fixed, yet unknown, resistance to be measured.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] *R*1, *R*2, and *R*3 are resistors of known resistance and the resistance of *R*2 is adjustable.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] The resistance *R*2 is adjusted until the bridge is "balanced" and no current flows through the galvanometer *Vg*.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] At this point, the potential difference between the two midpoints (B and D) will be zero.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] Therefore the ratio of the two resistances in the known leg (*R*2 / *R*1) is equal to the ratio of the two resistances in the unknown leg (*Rx* / *R*3).
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] If the bridge is unbalanced, the direction of the current indicates whether *R*2 is too high or too low.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] Detecting zero current with a galvanometer can be done to extremely high precision.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] Therefore, if *R*1, *R*2, and *R*3 are known to high precision, then *Rx* can be measured to high precision.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] Very small changes in *Rx* disrupt the balance and are readily detected.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] Alternatively, if *R*1, *R*2, and *R*3 are known, but *R*2 is not adjustable, the voltage difference across or current flow through the meter can be used to calculate the value of *Rx*, using Kirchhoff's circuit laws.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] This setup is frequently used in strain gauge and resistance thermometer measurements, as it is usually faster to read a voltage level off a meter than to adjust a resistance to zero the voltage.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] At the point of balance, both the voltage and the current between the two midpoints (B and D) are zero.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] Because of *V*D = *V*B, then *V*DC = *V*BC and *V*AD = *V*AB.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] ADC and ABC form two voltage dividers, with VG equal to the difference in output voltages.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] Due to *I*3 = *I**x* and *I*1 = *I*2 being proportional from Kirchhoff's current law, *I*3*I*2 / *I*1*I*x cancels out of the above equation.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] On the other hand, if the resistance of the galvanometer is high enough that *I**G* is negligible, it is possible to compute *R**x* from the three other resistor values and the supply voltage (*V**S*), or the supply voltage from all four resistor values.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] To do so, one has to work out the voltage from each potential divider and subtract one from the other.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] The Wheatstone bridge illustrates the concept of a difference measurement, which can be extremely accurate.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] Variations on the Wheatstone bridge can be used to measure capacitance, inductance, impedance and other quantities, such as the amount of combustible gases in a sample, with an explosimeter.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] The Kelvin bridge was specially adapted from the Wheatstone bridge for measuring very low resistances.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] In many cases, the significance of measuring the unknown resistance is related to measuring the impact of some physical phenomenon (such as force, temperature, pressure, etc.) which thereby allows the use of Wheatstone bridge in measuring those elements indirectly.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] The concept was extended to alternating current measurements by James Clerk Maxwell in 1865 and further improved as Blumlein bridge by Alan Blumlein in British Patent no.
[src:load-cells-strain/wheatstone-bridge] The Wheatstone bridge is the fundamental bridge, but there are other modifications that can be made to measure various kinds of resistances when the fundamental Wheatstone bridge is not suitable.
